Round 2!

While the relationships I had been exploring did pique my interest, I wanted to get a more personalised understanding of the data I had been gathering. Itâ€™s been just over a month since I last collected data for my Google Sheet, so itâ€™s entirely possible that Steamâ€™s idea of my â€œperfect gameâ€ has adapted since then. To investigate this possibility, I grouped up my entries by their timestamps to determine whether the entry was gathered for the first batch (Project 2) or the second batch (Project 4).

I wanted to create a unique visualisation for my third and final plot, so I created my own take on a â€œlollipop chartâ€ which compares the occurrences of each genre between each batch. Equivalent values across both batches are joined together, and greater values reach past lesser values to express the difference between the two.

I noticed the following details after an analysis of my plot:

  • Indie and Action games were much more prevalent in my second batch of data.
  • There were zero RPG games in my second batch of data.
  • Most other genres tended to maintain a similar number of occurrences throughout both batches of data
  • The average game in my second batch of data tended to fall under more genres at once than the average game in my first batch, meaning occurrence counts were slightly higher overall for games in the second batch.
